<paragraph id="3340217A40085F23FCC8FCA04AEA3BFE" blockId="31.[826,1442,810,924]" pageId="31" pageNumber="298">
<emphasis id="018BFD6840085F23FCC8FCA04CDC3B5D" box="[826,952,810,831]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="298">Etymology:</emphasis>
The name of this species is taken from the Spanish words ‘ 
<emphasis id="018BFD6840085F23FC0BFCC34B063B3C" box="[1017,1122,841,862]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="298">una mas</emphasis>
’, meaning more than one, because just when we had thought we had finished, we always seemed to discover yet another new species.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="3340217A40085F23FCC8FC3E4B3E3D90" blockId="31.[826,1442,948,1522]" pageId="31" pageNumber="298">
<emphasis id="018BFD6840085F23FCC8FC3E4C993BAB" box="[826,1021,948,969]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="298">Taxonomic notes:</emphasis>
The adult of 
<taxonomicName id="F4FF5AF940085F23FB69FC3E4A773BAB" authorityName="Rotheray &amp; Hancock &amp; Marcos-García" authorityYear="2007" box="[1179,1299,948,969]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Copestylum" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="31" pageNumber="298" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="unamas">
<emphasis id="018BFD6840085F23FB69FC3E4A773BAB" box="[1179,1299,948,969]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="298">C. unamas</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is similar to 
<taxonomicName id="F4FF5AF940085F23FCC8FC594CAE3B85" authorityName="Rotheray &amp; Hancock &amp; Marcos-García" authorityYear="2007" box="[826,970,978,1000]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Copestylum" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="31" pageNumber="298" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="triunfense">
<emphasis id="018BFD6840085F23FCC8FC594CAE3B85" box="[826,970,978,1000]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="298">C. triunfense</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in having a clear and distinct central vitta between the mouth and the base of the antennae. It differs from that species in having a yellow abdomen and yellow marks on the mesonotum. The form of the male genitalia is also distinct in having two teeth on the apical margin of the superior lobes, not separated by a deep groove, and only one pair of windows in the hypandrium. The early stages are very similar to other 
<taxonomicName id="F4FF5AF940085F23FC6FFB424B513CBF" authorityName="Rotheray &amp; Hancock &amp; Marcos-García" authorityYear="2007" box="[925,1077,1224,1245]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Copestylum" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="31" pageNumber="298" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="boqueronense">
<emphasis id="018BFD6840085F23FC6FFB424B513CBF" box="[925,1077,1224,1245]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="298">boqueronense</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group species. The main difference is in the posterior breathing tube that is smooth and shiny at the apex with, at most, only vague indications of punctures. Only 
<taxonomicName id="F4FF5AF940085F23FB70FAAE4B903D5B" authorityName="Rotheray &amp; Hancock &amp; Marcos-García" authorityYear="2007" box="[1154,1268,1316,1337]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Copestylum" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="31" pageNumber="298" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="triunfense">
<emphasis id="018BFD6840085F23FB70FAAE4B903D5B" box="[1154,1268,1316,1337]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="298">triunfense</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has a similar shiny apex to the posterior breathing tube. 
<taxonomicName id="F4FF5AF940085F23FADBFAC94AC53D3A" authorityName="Rotheray &amp; Hancock &amp; Marcos-García" authorityYear="2007" box="[1321,1441,1347,1368]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Copestylum" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="31" pageNumber="298" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="unamas">
<emphasis id="018BFD6840085F23FADBFAC94AC53D3A" box="[1321,1441,1347,1368]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="298">C. unamas</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from 
<taxonomicName id="F4FF5AF940085F23FC3AFAEB4B5E3D14" authorityName="Rotheray &amp; Hancock &amp; Marcos-García" authorityYear="2007" box="[968,1082,1377,1398]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Copestylum" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="31" pageNumber="298" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="triunfense">
<emphasis id="018BFD6840085F23FC3AFAEB4B5E3D14" box="[968,1082,1377,1398]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="298">triunfense</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in that the posterior breathing tube is parallel sided, and does widen basally and is about as wide as the pupal spiracles. In 
<taxonomicName id="F4FF5AF940085F23FAF6FA144A123DD1" authorityName="Rotheray &amp; Hancock &amp; Marcos-García" authorityYear="2007" box="[1284,1398,1438,1459]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Copestylum" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="31" pageNumber="298" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="triunfense">
<emphasis id="018BFD6840085F23FAF6FA144A123DD1" box="[1284,1398,1438,1459]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="298">triunfense</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the posterior breathing tube widens basally and is wider than the pupal spiracles.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="3340217A40085F23FCC8F9804BF73E5C" blockId="31.[826,1442,1546,1598]" pageId="31" pageNumber="298">
<emphasis id="018BFD6840085F23FCC8F9804CF13E7D" box="[826,917,1546,1567]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="298">Biology:</emphasis>
Reared from a larva found in a fallen, decaying bromeliad (
<taxonomicName id="F4FF5AF940085F23FC1BF9A24BEC3E5C" box="[1001,1160,1576,1598]" class="Liliopsida" family="Bromeliaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="31" pageNumber="298" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Bromeliaceae</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="3340217A40085F23FCC8F9F84A653EE5" blockId="31.[826,1281,1650,1671]" box="[826,1281,1650,1671]" pageId="31" pageNumber="298">
<emphasis id="018BFD6840085F23FCC8F9F84A653EE5" box="[826,1281,1650,1671]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="298">Other species from decaying bromeliads</emphasis>
</paragraph>
